On the edge of Saturn ü™ê‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Our Cassini spacecraft passes right by the edge of the rings of Saturn in this perspective that is never seen directly from Earth. This image was taken on Sept. 30, 2005, approximately 1.5 million miles (2.4 million km) from Saturn.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
In our skies, Saturn‚Äôs disk is always nearly fully illuminated by the Sun. From this point of view, nearly in the ring plane ‚Äî the Sun over to the right ‚Äî Cassini can see both lit and dark hemispheres, with the shadow of the rings on the northern hemisphere.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Image description: A black-and-white image of Saturn with the ring at eye level, imaged as a thin white line across the planet‚Äôs equator. The right side of the planet is illuminated by the Sun, with the shadow of the rings on the upper half of Saturn. Also visible are details of the subtle banded nature of Saturn‚Äôs atmosphere.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Credit: Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Space Science Institute‚Å£

caption.text:
We request the highest of fives. üñêÔ∏è‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Pulsar wind nebulas like this one are clouds of energetic X-ray-producing particles that are driven away from dead, collapsed stars. In this image, X-rays from our @NASAChandraXray observatory show up in gold and blue, while infrared rays spotted by the Victor M. Blanco 4-meter telescope are red and blue.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Astronomers estimate that light from the supernova explosion reached Earth about 1,700 years ago, or when the Mayan empire was flourishing and the Jin dynasty ruled China. However, by cosmic standards, this is one of the youngest supernova remnants in the Milky Way galaxy.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Image description: In this composite image, a pulsar, a pulsar wind nebula, and a low energy X-ray cloud combine to create an uncanny scene of a skeletal hand preparing to grab a glowing ember. The hand reaches up from the bottom of the image; X-rays observed by Chandra are seen as the ghostly blue flesh, with the white bones represented by pulsar wind. A bright white spot in the wrist is the pulsar itself. Just beyond the hand‚Äôs fingertips, near our upper right, is a mottled yellow and orange shape that appears to glow from within. This is the low-energy X-ray cloud observed by Chandra.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Credit: X-ray: NASA/CXC/SAO; Optical: NOIRLab/DECam; Image processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/J. Schmidt‚Å£

caption.text:
‚ÄúWhat is today but yesterday‚Äôs tomorrow?‚Äù Deep thoughts from the heart of a cosmic Krab, er, crab. ü¶Ä‚Å£
 ‚Å£
This close-up image of the Crab Nebula, originally released by @NASAHubble in 2016, reveals the beating heart of one of the most deeply-studied remnants of a supernova‚Äîin other words, the aftermath of an exploded star.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
The neutron star at the middle of the nebula (the rightmost of the two bright stars) is spinning 30 times a second, sending out pulses of radiation with clockwork regularity. The Crab Nebula, which first appeared in our skies about 1,000 years ago, is located about 6,500 light-years from Earth.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Image description: Stars and gas swirl through a misty image of the cosmos. Orange-red bands circle the outside of the image and snake through its middle; a handful of bright white stars are scattered throughout, especially just right of center.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Credits: NASA and ESA‚Å£

caption.text:
She doesn‚Äôt even go here!‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
When astronomers first studied the globular star cluster seen here in an image from @NASAHubble, they found that it appeared to be around 30% younger than other similar clusters in the Milky Way. If this cluster ‚Äì Palomar 12 ‚Äì was born in our galaxy, then it would be around the same age as other Milky Way globulars‚Ä¶ so it couldn‚Äôt be from here.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Further study revealed that Palomar 12 was actually ripped from its initial home, the Sagittarius Dwarf Elliptical galaxy, around 1.7 billion years ago by tidal interactions between its former home and our galaxy. The dwarf galaxy that Palomar 12 once called home is a satellite galaxy to ours, and closely orbits around us ‚Äî even occasionally passing through the plane of our galaxy.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Globular clusters like Palomar 12 can contain anywhere from tens of thousands to millions of stars, packed tightly together in dense clumps ranging from 50 to 450 light-years across. Because they contain so many stars, globular clusters are often the easiest clusters to spot in the night sky; skywatchers can see many of them with the unaided eye.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Image description: A cluster of stars is sprinkled out against the blackness of space. Larger, brighter stars ‚Äì some with diffraction spikes ‚Äì are somewhat arranged vertically along the middle of the image.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Credit: ESA, NASA‚Å£‚Å£

caption.text:
‚ÄúLook again at that dot. That‚Äôs here. That‚Äôs home. That‚Äôs us.‚Äù ‚Äî Carl Sagan, "Pale Blue Dot," 1994‚Å£‚Å£
 ‚Å£‚Å£
Our Voyager 1 spacecraft took this iconic image of Earth 35 years ago. Voyager 1 was so far away ‚Äî 3.7 billion miles (6 billion km) ‚Äî from the Sun that, from its vantage point, Earth was just a point of light about a pixel in size. Truly a ‚ÄúPale Blue Dot.‚Äù‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Mission managers commanded the spacecraft to look back toward home for a final time. It snapped a series of 60 images that were used to create the first ‚Äúfamily portrait‚Äù of our solar system.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Carl Sagan was a prominent planetary scientist who was a consultant and adviser to NASA beginning in the 1950s. He also was a member of the Voyager Imaging Team. He had the original idea in 1981 to use the cameras on one of the two Voyager spacecraft to image Earth. He realized that because the spacecraft were so far away the images might not show much. This was precisely why Sagan and other members of the Voyager team felt the images were needed ‚Äî they wanted humanity to see Earth‚Äôs vulnerability and that our home world is just a tiny, fragile speck in the cosmic ocean.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
After snapping the Pale Blue Dot and other ‚Äúfamily photos,‚Äù Voyager 1 powered off its cameras forever to save its energy for the long journey ahead. In August 2012, Voyager 1 entered interstellar space. It‚Äôs now the most distant human-made object ever.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Image description: Earth is a single, bright blue pixel in the vastness of space. Rays of sunlight scattered within the camera optics stretch across the scene, one of which happens to have intersected dramatically with Earth. The original image was taken on Feb. 14, 1990. What you see here is an updated version from 2020 using modern image-processing software and techniques.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Image credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
#NASA #Earth #PaleBlueDot #Astrophotography #Voyager #Space #Perspective

caption.text:
Goodbye, Earth. Hello, Moon üåù‚Å£
 ‚Å£
After a successful maneuver on Feb. 8, @FireflyAerospace‚Äôs Blue Ghost Mission 1 has departed Earth‚Äôs orbit and begun its four-day journey to the Moon‚Äôs orbit. Blue Ghost will spend about 16 days in lunar orbit before descending to the surface of the Moon on Mar. 2.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Blue Ghost successfully launched from @NASAKennedy on Jan. 15. Since launching more than four weeks ago, the lunar lander has performed dozens of health tests generating 15 gigabytes of data. All 10 NASA science and technology payloads onboard are healthy.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Blue Ghost is a part of our lunar delivery initiative to send NASA science and technology to the Moon ahead of crewed Artemis missions.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Image description: Firefly‚Äôs Blue Ghost lander recently captured this image of Earth. An image of Earth is also reflected off the solar panel on the lander. The Moon can be seen on the horizon above Earth. Firefly‚Äôs X-band antenna and NASA‚Äôs Lunar Environment Heliospheric X-ray Imager (LEXI) payload are visible on the top deck of the lander. The background is filled with the darkness of space.‚Å£
 ‚Å£

caption.text:
Delivery from the universe! üíê
 
A bouquet blooming with thousands of stars is captured in this image of the star-forming region 30 Doradus. This composite image combines X-ray data from our @NASAChandraXray observatory (in blue and green) with optical data from @NASAHubble (in yellow) and radio data from the Atacama Large Millimeter/submillimeter Array (in red).
 
Since 1999, our Chandra X-ray Observatory has been studying the universe from low Earth orbit. Chandra, the world's most powerful X-ray telescope, has given astronomers new insights into black holes, distant galaxies, and stellar explosions.
 
Image description: A composite image of a star-forming region of space known as 30 Doradus, which is shaped like a bouquet or a maple leaf. X-ray wind and gas takes the shape of a massive purple and pink bouquet with an extended central flower. The hazy, mottled shape occupies much of the image, positioned just to the left of center. Inside the purple and pink gas and wind cloud are red and orange veins and pockets of bright white light. The hazy purple and pink bouquet is surrounded by glowing dots of green, white, orange, and red. A second mottled purple cloud, which resembles a ring of smoke, floats in the lower-right corner.
 
Credit: X-ray (Chandra): NASA/CXC/Penn State Univ./L. Townsley et al.; Infrared (Spitzer): NASA/JPL-CalTech/SST; Optical (Hubble): NASA/STScI/HST; Radio (Atacama Large Millimeter/submillimeter Array): ESO/NAOJ/NRAO/ALMA; Image Processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/J. Schmidt, N. Wolk, K. Arcand

caption.text:
Look up, let your hair down ‚Äì howl if you like ‚Äì for it‚Äôll be a full moon!‚Å£
 ‚Å£
After cozying up to Venus, Jupiter, and Mars earlier this month, the Moon reaches peak illumination on Feb. 12.‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Looking at the Moon with only your eyes, you‚Äôll see mostly areas of white and gray. The gray patches are solidified volcanic lava flows. When the Moon was young, its interior was still molten, and magma would erupt onto its surface. The lighter-colored areas are called the highlands, and show the earliest crust on the Moon, dominated by a type of rock called anorthosite.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
What you see on the Moon with just your eyes will vary depending on your eyesight. Give yourself plenty of time for your eyes to adjust and look carefully. Looking with binoculars or a telescope will reveal more details, like mountain ridges and crater chains.‚Å£‚Å£
 ‚Å£
For better viewing of craters and mountains, try phases other than the full moon. The shadows on the surface will be more pronounced, and help distinguish features you might otherwise miss.‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Image description: In this picture from May 25, 2021, the nearly full moon rises over National Harbor in Fort Washington, Maryland. The Moon is just under the tip of the triangle shape formed by a structure. Some buildings and water can be seen in the background, while a few people are in the dimly lit foreground.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Credit: NASA/Bill Ingalls‚Å£‚Å£

caption.text:
The Bend & Snap üíÖ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
We don‚Äôt know the rate of return on scoring a dinner invitation with this information, but what you see here is the light from a distant galaxy bending around a closer one. The @EuropeanSpaceAgency‚Äôs Euclid telescope snapped this observation of a rare phenomenon called an Einstein ring.‚Å£

The gravity of this elliptical galaxy, which is around 590 million light-years from Earth, acts as a lens. It magnifies a much more distant bright galaxy, some 4.42 billion light-years away, into a ring of light. ‚Å£

Developed by ESA with contributions from @NASA, Euclid is surveying the cosmos to help us understand the dark side of the universe. We can‚Äôt wait to see what it reveals next!‚Å£
Image descriptions:‚Å£
 ‚Å£
1. The large, hazy oval of elliptical galaxy NGC 6505 illuminates the center of this image from the European Space Agency‚Äôs Euclid mission. At the heart of the galaxy is a small bright spot surrounded by a thin white circle, which is a magnified view of a much more distant galaxy. The view is also filled with countless colorful stars and galaxies of various sizes and shapes amidst the blackness of space. Thin spikes of light extend from the brightest stars due to the observatory‚Äôs optics.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
2. A thin ring of a perfect circular shape and a piercingly bright white disc in its middle are the protagonists of this image. They ‚Å£stand out against a uniformly colored background of a hazy dark grey. The ring appears as if it was a faint brush stroke, where at four evenly spaced spots more pressure was applied on the brush. These stand out in the ring as four brighter and thicker spots. The white disc within the ring gives the impression of a gaping hole in the image, through its stark contrast to the dark background.‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Credit: ESA/Euclid/Euclid Consortium/NASA, image processing by J.-C. Cuillandre, T. Li; CC BY-SA 3.0 IGO‚Å£
 ‚Å£
#EinsteinRing #ESAEuclid #GravitationalLensing #Galaxy #Gravity #Space

All the stars are closer ‚ú®
 
Orbiting Earth 16 times a day, the International Space Station is about 250 miles (400 km) closer to the stars than the rest of us back on Earth. From the @ISS, our @NASAAstronauts get a unique perspective on landmarks and cities around the globe‚Äîincluding New Orleans, the site of this year's #SuperBowl.
 
Astronaut @astro_pettit captured this image of New Orleans on Oct. 26, 2024; Pettit has taken countless pictures from low Earth orbit as part of his "Science of Opportunity" since lifting off to the station last September. Visit nasa.gov/iss to learn more about what we're discovering aboard the orbiting laboratory!
 
Image description: An image of New Orleans as seen from the International Space Station at night. The city's lights stand out in bright white, with key streets and blocks standing out. The Mississippi River can be seen snaking through the city center, with Lake Pontchartrain marking an end to the city's lights on their northern border.

Credit: NASA/Don Pettit

caption.text:
Looking to the fuschia üíñ‚Å£
‚Å£
Our @NASAChandraXray observatory captured this colorful scene of two spiral galaxies merging. This galaxy pair is located about 250 million light-years away and can be found in the constellation of Serpens. ‚Å£
‚Å£
The collision of the two spiral galaxies happened about 700 million years ago, sparking an enormous burst of star formation. About 200 huge star clusters reside in a packed, dusty region about 5,000 light-years across‚Äîabout 5% of the Milky Way‚Äôs diameter. The amount of gas in this tiny region is equal to all of the gas in the entire Milky Way. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description: This composite image features an ultra-luminous infrared galaxy, surrounded by a soft, rose-pink cloud of X-ray gas. Here, a single, bright, golden white dot sits at the center of the image. The rose-pink cloud surrounding the dot appears soft and airy, like cotton candy. Upon close inspection, feint orange veins can be discerned, marbling the X-ray gas cloud seen with Chandra. Surrounding the gas cloud are other distant galaxies and stars, set against the blackness of space. Most are orange or white, and range from tiny specks to small glowing ovals.‚Å£
‚Å£
Credit: X-ray: NASA/CXC/SAO; Optical: NASA/ESA/STScI; Infrared: NASA/ESA/CSA/STScI; Image Processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/L. Frattare, J. Major ‚Å£

caption.text:
We got twins! Twins! üå™Ô∏èüå™Ô∏è

These looping funnel clouds are half a light-year in length‚Äîbut don't worry, they're not touching down near Earth anytime soon. They're swirling 5,000 light-years away in the Lagoon Nebula, which can be found in the constellation Sagittarius.

Our @NASAHubble telescope spotted these twisters nearly 30 years ago, based on observations collected from July to September of 1995. Like tornadoes back on Earth, the sharp differences in temperature between the hot surface of the nebula's clouds and their cold interior (combined with the pressure of sunlight) may twist these tornadoes into the shapes you see here.

Image description: A nebula, lit in soft shades of blue, green and yellow, is intersected by a pair of much darker funnel clouds, which reach from the top-left to the bottom-right of the image. A red, slightly pixellated star shines through the cloud in the bottom right.

Credit: NASA and A. Caulet (ST-ECF, ESA)
